#Text=Ozma 's Prisoner
#Text=The boy was so bewildered by this calamity that he made no resistance at all .
#Text=He knew very well he was guilty , but it surprised him that Ozma also knew it .
#Text=He wondered how she had found out so soon that he had picked the six-leaved clover .
#Text=He handed his basket to Scraps and said :
#Text=" Keep that , until I get out of prison .

#Text=It 's in patch-time , which is much superior to rag-time , and I 've composed it in honor of the Patchwork Girl , who has just arrived .

#Text= How did you know I had arrived ? " asked Scraps , much interested .

column1: #Text=" It 's my business to know who 's coming , for I 'm the Guardian of the Gate .
#Text=" Good gracious !

#Text=A prisoner ?  cried the little man , jumping up from his chair .

column1: #Text=" Ah ; I hope his fault is as small as himself , " said the Guardian of the Gate .
#Text=" But what can he have done , and what made him do it ? "
#Text=" Ca n't say , " replied the soldier .
#Text=" All I know is that he has broken the Law . "
#Text=" But no one ever does that ! "
#Text=" Then he must be innocent , and soon will be released .

#Text=Since I came to the Land of Oz no one has ever been arrested or imprisoned -- until Ojo broke the Law .

_	_	_	_

#Text= Seems to me that girl Ruler of yours is making a big fuss over nothing , " remarked Scraps , tossing her yarn hair out of her eyes with a jerk of her patched head .

column1: #Text=" I do n't know what Ojo has done , but it could n't be anything very bad , for you and I were with him all the time . "
#Text=The Shaggy Man made no reply to this speech and presently the Patchwork Girl forgot all about Ojo in her admiration of the wonderful city she had entered .
#Text=They soon separated from the Munchkin boy , who was led by the Soldier with the Green Whiskers down a side street toward the prison .
#Text=Ojo felt very miserable and greatly ashamed of himself , but he was beginning to grow angry because he was treated in such a disgraceful manner .

#Text=Instead of entering the splendid Emerald City as a respectable traveler who was entitled to a welcome and to hospitality , he was being brought in as a criminal , handcuffed and in a robe that told all he met of his deep disgrace .
#Text=Ojo was by nature gentle and affectionate and if he had disobeyed the Law of Oz it was to restore his dear Unc Nunkie to life .
#Text=His fault was more thoughtless than wicked , but that did not alter the fact that he had committed a fault .

#Text=At first he had felt sorrow and remorse , but the more he thought about the unjust treatment he had received -- unjust merely because he considered it so -- the more he resented his arrest , blaming Ozma for making foolish laws and then punishing folks who broke them .
#Text=Only a six-leaved clover !
#Text=A tiny green plant growing neglected and trampled under foot .
#Text=What harm could there be in picking it ?
#Text=Ojo began to think Ozma must be a very bad and oppressive Ruler for such a lovely fairyland as Oz .
#Text=The Shaggy Man said the people loved her ; but how could they ?
